### Start here: what is a "bean"?

In Spring, a **bean** is just a Java object that Spring creates and manages for you. That is the entire definition. If you annotate a class with @Component, @Service, @Repository, or @Controller, you are telling Spring: "Please create one instance of this class and keep it available for the whole application."

By default, Spring creates exactly **one** instance per bean (called singleton scope) and reuses it everywhere. So when five different classes all @Autowire the same EmailService, they all get the exact same object — Spring creates it once and shares it.

**The simplest possible Spring bean:**
```java
@Service
public class GreetingService {
    public String greet(String name) {
        return "Hello, " + name;
    }
}
```
That is a bean. Spring creates it, and anyone can @Autowire it.

### Dependency Injection — the "handing over" step

Dependency Injection means Spring automatically provides the objects your class needs. Instead of you writing `this.emailService = new EmailService()` inside your class, Spring looks at your constructor and says "this class needs an EmailService, let me find one and pass it in."

**Before Spring (manual, painful):**
```java
public class OrderService {
    private EmailService emailService;
    public OrderService() {
        this.emailService = new EmailService(); // you create it yourself
    }
}
```
**With Spring (automatic, clean):**
```java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    private final EmailService emailService;
    public OrderService(EmailService emailService) { // Spring passes it in
        this.emailService = emailService;
    }
}
```
Spring sees the constructor, finds the EmailService bean it already created, and passes it automatically. You never call `new EmailService()`. Spring handles it.

### The lifecycle — what Spring does between @Service and your method running

Here is the full sequence Spring follows every time it creates a bean. Read it like a recipe:

**Step 1 — Read the recipe (BeanDefinition)**
Spring scans your code and finds all @Service, @Component etc. classes. It builds a recipe for each one: what class is it, what does it need, how should it be created. At this point, no objects exist yet — Spring is just planning.

**Step 2 — Adjust the recipe if needed (BeanFactoryPostProcessor)**
Before creating anything, Spring allows recipe modifications. This is how ${property.value} placeholders in your @Value annotations get replaced with real values from application.properties. You rarely write this yourself, but Spring Boot uses it heavily internally.

**Step 3 — Build the object (Constructor)**
Spring calls your constructor. The object exists now, but its fields are empty. If you print `emailService` inside the constructor, it is null.

**Step 4 — Give it what it needs (Injection)**
Spring fills in all @Autowired fields, @Value fields, and setter injections. After this step, all dependencies are populated.

**Step 5 — Tell it who it is (Aware interfaces)**
Optional step. If your bean implements BeanNameAware, Spring tells it its own registered name. If it implements ApplicationContextAware, Spring gives it access to the whole container. Most beans never need this.

**Step 6 — Let it warm up (@PostConstruct)**
If you have a method annotated @PostConstruct, Spring calls it now. This is your chance to do setup work that needs the injected dependencies — open a connection, preload a cache, validate configuration. This is the most commonly used lifecycle hook.

**Step 7 — Wrap it if needed (BeanPostProcessor)**
Spring checks if any BeanPostProcessors want to wrap this bean. This is where @Transactional, @Async, and AOP features work — Spring replaces your bean with a proxy that adds extra behaviour. From this point on, when someone @Autowires this service, they get the proxy, not your original object.

**Step 8 — Bean is ready and in use**
Your bean is now available. Every @Autowired injection of this type gets this (possibly proxied) instance.

**Step 9 — Cleanup on shutdown (@PreDestroy)**
When the application shuts down, Spring calls @PreDestroy methods. Close database connections, stop background threads, flush buffers.

### @PostConstruct — the most important lifecycle hook

@PostConstruct marks a method that Spring calls after the bean is fully built and all dependencies are injected.

**When you need it:** anything that requires your injected fields to be ready — opening connections, loading data, validating config.

**Golden rule:** never do this work in the constructor. In the constructor, your @Autowired fields are still null. In @PostConstruct, they are all populated.

```java
@Service
public class CacheService {
    @Autowired
    private DatabaseRepository db;

    private List<String> cache;

    public CacheService() {
        // db is NULL here — do not use it
    }

    @PostConstruct
    public void loadCache() {
        cache = db.findAll(); // safe — db is injected before this runs
    }
}
```

### @PreDestroy — the cleanup hook

@PreDestroy marks a method Spring calls when the application is shutting down. Use it to release resources your bean holds.

**Important rule for prototype beans:** Spring calls @PreDestroy on singleton beans. For prototype-scoped beans (a new instance per request), Spring does NOT call @PreDestroy. If your prototype holds a resource, you are responsible for closing it yourself.

### Bean scopes — how many instances does Spring create?

By default, Spring creates ONE instance of each bean for the entire app (singleton). But you can change this:

**@Scope("singleton")** — default. One shared instance. Everyone gets the same object.
**@Scope("prototype")** — new instance every time someone asks for it. Like calling new each time.
**@Scope("request")** — one instance per HTTP request. Useful in web apps.
**@Scope("session")** — one instance per user session.

Singleton is right 95% of the time. Use prototype when your bean holds per-user state.

### The scope mismatch trap — very common beginner mistake

Imagine you have a prototype bean called `Cart` (one per user) and you inject it into a singleton `CheckoutService`.

Spring creates `CheckoutService` ONCE. At that moment, it injects ONE `Cart` instance. That same Cart is now stuck inside CheckoutService forever. Every user's checkout goes through the same Cart object — their items mix together. That is a bug.

**Why it happens:** the singleton is created once, so injection happens once. Prototype scope is irrelevant after that single injection moment.

**The fix:** instead of injecting `Cart` directly, inject `ObjectFactory<Cart>`. Each time you call `objectFactory.getObject()`, Spring creates a fresh `Cart`.

### @Qualifier and @Primary — "which one do you want?"

What happens when you have two classes that implement the same interface?

```java
interface PaymentService { void pay(); }

@Service class StripePayment implements PaymentService { ... }
@Service class PayPalPayment implements PaymentService { ... }
```

Now if you @Autowire `PaymentService`, Spring panics — it has two candidates and does not know which to pick. You get a `NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException` at startup.

**@Primary** says: "When in doubt, use this one."
**@Qualifier("name")** says: "I specifically want this one, at this injection point."

@Qualifier always wins over @Primary. Use @Primary for the default implementation. Use @Qualifier when you need a specific non-default one.

### @DependsOn — "do this first"

Sometimes one bean needs another bean to have run its setup before it starts — but without actually injecting it. Example: a database migration bean must run before any repository bean starts.

@DependsOn("migrationRunner") tells Spring: "create and initialize migrationRunner before creating me." No injection happens. It is purely about order.

### Circular dependencies — when A needs B and B needs A

This is a design problem that Spring makes visible. If OrderService needs NotificationService and NotificationService needs OrderService, Spring cannot create either one first — both need the other to exist.

With constructor injection, Spring fails at startup with a clear error. Good — fail fast.

The real fix is not a Spring trick. It is a design fix: extract a third class (like an EventBus or shared helper) that both depend on, breaking the circle.

### 60-second mental model

Spring creates your objects (construction), fills in what they need (injection), lets them do setup (@PostConstruct), wraps them in proxies if needed (BeanPostProcessor), then serves them to the rest of your app. On shutdown it calls @PreDestroy for cleanup. Prototype beans are created fresh each time but Spring does not clean them up — you do. When you have two beans of the same type, use @Primary for the default or @Qualifier for an explicit pick. Circular dependencies are a design smell — extract a shared class instead of patching with @Lazy.

