conceptual.answer:
@Primary on a bean makes it the default for any unqualified injection of that type. @Qualifier("name") at a specific injection point says "I want this exact one." They do not conflict — @Qualifier always wins over @Primary at any injection point where it is used.

Use @Primary when one implementation covers 90% of cases (the real PaymentGateway vs a test stub). Use @Qualifier when two real implementations coexist and you need explicit control at specific injection points (Stripe vs PayPal — both are real, both are used).

One dangerous pattern: @Primary on a stub without @Profile("test"). In production, both the real service and the stub are registered, @Primary silently makes the stub the default, and real functionality is replaced with no-ops.

