conceptual.answer:
@Profile("name") is actually shorthand for @Conditional(ProfileCondition.class) — it activates a bean only when a specific named profile is active.

@Conditional accepts a custom Condition class with a matches() method where you can put any logic: check a property value, check if a class is on the classpath, check the operating system, check if another bean exists.

@ConditionalOnProperty, @ConditionalOnClass, @ConditionalOnMissingBean (Spring Boot autoconfigure) are all built on @Conditional.

Use @Profile for environment switching (dev vs prod vs test). Use @Conditional for feature flags, optional integrations, and "only if X library is present on the classpath" checks.

